//! disclosed reason (its own header): re-deriving expectations through the
//! SAME query, in the SAME sync execution, that produced the artifact under
//! test would make the test agree with itself by construction. That
//! reasoning is correct for what THAT proof checks -- "does the generated
//! table match a human's independent reading of the ontology" -- but it
//! leaves a gap: a hand-transcribed array is authored once and never
//! auto-updates, so it cannot detect the case where `ontology.ttl` changes
//! LATER and the generated artifacts fall behind it.
//!
//! This proof closes that gap by checking a DIFFERENT thing, not the same
//! thing more strictly: whether `src/praxis_core_refusal_table.rs` and
//! `docs/praxis_core_refusal_taxonomy.md`, as they actually sit on disk
//! right now, still agree with what `pxc:RefusalScenario` individuals say
//! RIGHT NOW. It cannot and does not claim to validate "is the ontology
//! itself correct" -- nothing can, that is definitional -- only "has the
//! checked-in generated artifact silently drifted from the ontology since
//! it was last written."
//!
//! ## Why this is not the same tautology the sibling proof's header warns about
//!
//! 1. Asymmetric freshness, not identical-execution self-agreement.
//!    `refusal_taxonomy_rs.tmpl` writes its output under
//!    `freeze_policy: checksum` (see `src/write.rs`'s `check_freeze`): once a
//!    consumer hand-edits `src/praxis_core_refusal_table.rs`, further syncs
//!    silently skip regenerating it (protecting the hand edit) rather than
//!    erroring -- the const table can legitimately go stale relative to a
//!    LATER `ontology.ttl` edit while `ggen sync run` still exits 0. This
//!    proof template carries NO `freeze_policy` of its own: its `LIVE_*`
//!    array below is re-baked from a live query against whatever
//!    `ontology.ttl` says at the moment THIS file is (re)generated. So the
//!    two sides of every assertion below are not guaranteed to come from the
//!    same sync execution -- one (`RS_CONTENT`/`MD_CONTENT`, via
//!    `include_str!`) is whatever was last actually written to disk, frozen
//!    or not; the other (`LIVE_*`) is always "right now." A hand-transcribed
//!    expectation frozen at authoring time cannot distinguish those two
//!    states from each other; this one can, and fails loudly when they
//!    diverge.
//! 2. Independent rendering, not the same substitution checked twice.
//!    This template's own for-loop over the `scenarios` SPARQL result is a
//!    SEPARATE Tera render pass from `refusal_taxonomy_rs.tmpl`'s own loop
//!    over the identical query. A field-mapping bug local to ONE of the
//!    two templates (wrong variable, dropped row, stray whitespace) produces
//!    a generated-table string that this proof's independently-rendered
//!    `LIVE_*` values will not match, and the assertions below fail --
//!    mirroring the same "two independent renderings checked against each
//!    other" principle the sibling proof already uses between its RS and MD
//!    assertions, extended here to a freshly-queried third rendering instead
//!    of a third hand-typed one.
//!
//! ## Honest scope
//!
//! This still compares rendered TEXT via substring search, not a parsed
//! Rust/Markdown AST -- the same limitation the sibling proof has. It does
//! not attempt real-`praxis-core`-crate fidelity (that is the sibling
